				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Collision data is quite different from name table data, so you shouldn't get too hung up on treating them similarly. Name tables are often read in their entirety and copied to specific locations in video RAM because that's where the NES expects them to be so they can be rendered to the screen. Collision data on the other hand is a part of your game's engine, it's meaningful only to the game logic you're programming, so the NES couldn't care less about how or where it's stored. Unless it's compressed or it can be modified during gameplay (e.g. blocks can be destroyed), there's no point in copying it anywhere, you can access it using pointers and indexes formed with math formulas applied to pixel coordinates directly from PRG-ROM.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
